&lt;h3&gt;5. Professional registration&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The apprenticeship will provide the knowledge, skills and behaviours to apply to become Members of the Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors or the Chartered Institution of Civil Engineering Surveyors.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;6. Duration&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This apprenticeship will typically be undertaken over five years.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;7. Level&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This Apprenticeship Standard is at Level 6.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h3&gt;8. Review date&lt;/h3&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This Apprenticeship Standard will be reviewed after three years.&lt;/p&gt;

occupationalSummary:
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;A career contributing to the environment in which you live.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Geospatial and mapping specialists are critical in a wide range of activities which seek to improve the world we live in. They should be involved in any work that involves a positional aspect, and their influence stretches far and wide. The management of limited resources is crucial for the future of the planet and so quality information of the location of resources in a form which can be easily analysed is vital. Development projects to improve infrastructure required detailed information of the current situation in order to design solutions which are environmentally sustainable.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;The occupation is found in the private sector, both on land and at sea, but the public sector requirements still exist.&amp;nbsp; The 21st century has seen enormous changes to the profession as it is a fast adopter of technology in every way.&amp;nbsp; Employers therefore include land, air and offshore companies, civil engineering contractors and consultancies, construction companies, railway operators, local authorities, central government, the military, multinational corporations, cartographic publishers, suppliers of computer-based mapping technology, utility companies and more.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;The broad purpose of the occupation is to provide geospatial data of high precision and to state it is quality.&amp;nbsp; Decisions made using the data will only be as good as that data quality; if it is incorrect then anything resulting from it will be unreliable.&amp;nbsp;The data can take many forms with the traditional 2D map or plan as one of the simplest products. We live in a 3D world and so 3D data and visualisations are commonplace.&amp;nbsp; The process is, therefore, to make measurements of position using a number of techniques varying from angles and distances using traditional surveyors’ instruments through automated laser scanning, photography and global satellite navigation systems (GNSS).&amp;nbsp; Such data is processed using CAD systems, GIS systems and more specialist software to handle the vast amount of data created (Big Data) to produce models which can be interrogated to provide the information required.&amp;nbsp; An example is Building Information Modelling (BIM) for a full digital representation (digital twin) of assets which is used to reduce the cost of its future management.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;In their daily work, geospatial specialists will work on international projects as well as more local improvements such as renewable energy, transport, and residential developments. However, their expertise is also invaluable to other industries such as entertainment with film, TV, computer simulation and gaming and the Metaverse.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;Historically, specialists in this area were found in the military, but following the Second World War there was a need to properly map all the countries of the world and the huge scale of construction to repair the war damage led to a high demand and commercial organisations as well government departments took on the roles. The exploration and development of offshore hydrocarbon assets in the 1970s saw demands for hydrographic surveyors.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;An employer in this occupation will work with geospatial specialists, interact with other professionals to determine their requirements and to design, manage and production of the resulting data model.&amp;nbsp; This will involve determining the geographical coordinate reference system, the instrumentation and methods of data collection and processing to meet the quality requirements of the project.&amp;nbsp; This will include a quality control system to ensure the final product meets the specification with due regard to health, safety and environmental requirements.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p class=&quot;MsoNormal&quot;&gt;There is currently a global demand for geospatial specialists and the knowledge, skills and behaviours are transferrable worldwide.&amp;nbsp; The geospatial profession is fast moving and continues to evolve with technological developments which make it an exciting career that contributes to a better world.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
